author: BBC News
description:
Hamas has recalled about 7,000 members of its security forces to reassert control over areas of Gaza recently vacated by Israeli troops, according to local sources.
 
The mobilisation order was reportedly issued via phone calls and text messages which said the aim was to "cleanse Gaza of outlaws and collaborators with Israel" and told fighters to report within 24 hours.
 
Reports from Gaza suggest that armed Hamas units have already deployed across several districts, some wearing civilian clothes and others in the blue uniforms of the Gaza police.
 
It comes as a ceasefire between Israel and Hamas enters its second day, and currently seems to be holding.

author: BBC News
description:
President Emmanuel Macron has asked Sébastien Lecornu to return as French prime minister only four days after he stood down from the post, sparking a week of high drama and political turmoil in the country.
 
Macron made the announcement late on Friday, hours after meeting all the main parties together at the Élysée Palace, except the leaders of the far right and far left.
 
Lecornu's return came as a surprise, as he said on national TV only two days ago he was not "chasing the job" and his "mission is over".
 
It is not even certain he will be able to form a government, but he will have to hit the ground running. The new prime minister faces a deadline on Monday to put next year's budget before parliament.

author: BBC News
description:
Eighteen people are missing after a blast at a military explosives manufacturing facility in Tennessee, US, on Friday.
 
Initial reports indicated that 19 people were missing, but Humphreys County Sheriff Chris Davis later said one person initially believed to be on site had been located at home.
 
The plant in Bucksnort, Tennessee -  56 miles (90km) south west of Nashville - specialises in the development, manufacture, handling and storage of explosives. The cause of the blast remains unclear.
 
Aerial video from the scene showed charred debris, smouldering vehicles and little remaining of the facility, which is owned by Accurate Energetic Systems.

author: BBC News
description:
Thousands of Palestinians have begun returning to Gaza’s north, after the ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas came into effect on Friday.
 
As part of the first phase of the agreement, Hamas has until 12:00 local time (10:00 BST) on Monday to release Israeli hostages, while Israel is set to release around 250 Palestinian prisoners and 1,700 detainees from Gaza.
 
US President Donald Trump said Hamas is gathering the Israeli hostages “now”, adding that he's confident the Gaza deal he helped broker will "hold”.
 
For the Palestinians heading north, they return to territory that has been largely destroyed by two years of war, including nearly three-quarters of all buildings in Gaza City.
